[2] Cholera - Niger
Date: Fri 3 Sep 2021
Source: Channels TV [edited]
https://www.channelstv.com/2021/09/03/death-toll-in-niger-republic-cholera-outbreak-rises-to-104/


An epidemic of cholera that has struck 6 regions in southern Niger has claimed 104 lives, the health ministry said on Fri, 3 Sep 2021. It reported that 2874 cases of the water-borne disease had been recorded in the capital Niamey and 5 other regions -- Maradi, Zinder, Dosso, Tahoua and Tillaberi.

The toll as of 19 Aug 2021 stood at 35 fatalities out of 845 cases. But the number of dead hit 104 on 1 Sep 2021, with a "fatality rate of 4%", the health ministry said in a statement. Most infections are among people aged between 15 and 37, the ministry said. The authorities are working with Doctors Without Borders (MSF), the UN, and EU on a prevention campaign, including disinfection of village wells and the distribution of water purification tablets.

Cholera is spread by eating or drinking food or water contaminated by human feces. The disease is treated with rehydration and antimicrobials and prevented with better hygiene and sanitation.

Niger's last epidemic of cholera was in 2018, when 78 people died out of a caseload of 3824 patients, according to the UN's WHO. The latest outbreak coincides with severe flooding, which increases exposure to cholera bacteria.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Niger or the Niger, officially the Republic of the Niger, is a landlocked country in West Africa named after the Niger River. Niger is bordered by Nigeria to the south, where, as reported below, a large outbreak of cholera has been occurring especially in the north of Nigeria.

